arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThroughout the world, vulnerable people are being deceived into entering abusive journeys. Whether in the organ trade, exploitative labour businesses or forced criminality, their lives will never be the same. This book traces the journey of victims/survivors of modern slavery and human trafficking into and within the UK, from recruitment to representation to (re)integration. Using global comparative case studies, it discusses recruitment tactics and demand, prevention in supply chains, issues with effective legal protection and care services and vulnerability to re-trafficking. It also examines the ideological misrepresentation of vulnerable migrants and victims/survivors in media, the film industry, legislation and more. Rooted in diverse practitioner experience, disciplines and empirical research, this book bridges the experience-research-practice-policy gap by bringing to the fore survivors’ voices. In doing so, it offers crucial suggestions for better public awareness, policies and practices that will impact interventions in the UK and beyond.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aHuman trafficking victimszGreat Britain. 0aHuman trafficking victims. 0aHuman traffickingzGreat Britain. 0aHuman trafficking. 0aSlaveryzGreat Britain. 0aSlavery. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Social Services & Welfare.2bisacsh1 aAnstiss, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAriyo, Debbie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarlow, Craig H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrachou, Anta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurch, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voca